bug.short_desc: support embedding wiki content

long_desc.thetext: Any news on this? We are moving more documentation to the wiki and the lack of navigation is a real problem.

This idea is called "Transclusion" and goes back to the origins of hyper-text.
http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transclusion
I think it would be awesome if one could transclude a whole wiki page or maybe even just one section. I belive the transcluded content should look a little special and should have an automatically generated link back to the original page.
We should have a built-in function to do this. Something like:
wiki_include("Page Name", "Section Name");

Cool, I didn't know that word until now :) Transclusion seems like the perfect way for us to overly navigation on wiki content without sacrificing any wikiness (as long as the black bar with the "edit" is retained, which it would be with the simple and naive implementation that I'm suggesting). But I really like Ward's way of doing this and it would enable useful things like embedding a particular important FAQ entry on a download page instead of doing what we currently do: replicating the content and having the HTML page go out of date.

Sorry I'm repeating what others have said, but here was my way of saying it:
The Problem
In short, the more you use the Eclipse wiki, the more visitors get lost. Our goal is to have a nice clean site structure that uses web pages where the content is relatively static and wiki pages where it is changing all the time:
http://eclipse.org/higgins Higgins Home
Charter webpage Team-leaders webpage FAQ webpage Architecture(<--imagine this in red) wiki page
Clicking on the left-hand side things like Charter, Team-leaders, etc. that lead to web pages works fine, because the left-hand navigation rail is always there.
But clicking on the red Architecture button will immediately make you feel dazed and confused. Why? Because the left-hand navigation rail is missing! Worse than missing, it has been replaced by another left-hand rail that has nothing to do with the Higgins project and how you got to where you are. The more sub-pages we add to the wiki, the queasier folks feel.
Work-Around
The horrible hack to work around this is that we try to remember to put a See Also section at the bottom of every wiki page that at least gets you back to the Higgins Home. But it just feels terrible. We get complaints like Eclipse navigation sucks.
There must be a better solution.
-Paul
We'll be discussing this at our next Phoenix meeting - Jan 10
Any news?

Any news on this?
Scott: was there any outcome of my inquiry about this at the last board meeting?
Denis: am I wrong in assuming that this would be trivial to implement on the Phoneix end?

Hi Mik,
(In reply to comment #7) > Any news on this? > > Scott: was there any outcome of my inquiry about this at the last board > meeting?
No. The Board meeting agenda for Jan didn't include this issue.
I personally wasn't involved with the Phoenix meeting referred to in comment #5 and so (still) don't know the outcome of the discussion there.

Unfortunately it's not as simple as your code in comment 0.
The index_plain.php would have to be executed by the web server, as the pages are stored in database. This is a problem for two reasons:
1. Our security policy doesn't allow our web server to establish web connections, not even to itself.
2. This type of exercice (the web server calling the web server) brought our entire site down at EclipseCON last year, as our number of web connections increased dramatically faster than the number of human clients. As such, it increases our ability to be "taken down" by a DoS attack.
From here I can think of three solutions -- none of which I particularly like.
1. We implement some form of plugin for MediaWiki where a PHP script could be include() 'd inside another PHP script on a different vhost. This would (unfortunately) tie www.eclipse.org and wiki.eclipse.org to the same set of physical servers (or physical backend storage), which is not a desirable scenario. I have searched for a MediaWiki extension that would allow this, but have found none.
2. We write a Phoenix method to transclude a Wiki page. The Phoenix method would fetch the Wiki page directly from the database. This would be fairly easy to set the page's plain text; however, all the Wiki markup would need to be parsed and interpreted, which would repeat a lot of Wiki code, and could break if we upgrade the Wiki to a new version which has database schema changes. Yuk.
3. We run a script that simply crawls the wiki website and saves the generated html contents in static html files that can be included inside Phoenix. As the wiki grows, this will consume lots of disk space and be a burden on the servers as many pages get checked out for no reason. Not really a good solution.
I quickly tried an iframe, but Wiki "breaks out" of the iframe when it is accessed.
I'll try to think of more solutions.

Um, maybe #9 is why Ted Nelson, the inventor of hypertext and transclusion of it, never got his own system, xanadu, working.
http://www.wired.com/wired/3.06/xanadu.html

So I wrote an demo on how transclusion could be done with javascript and an IFrame and have setup a demo at:
http://www.eclipse.org/phoenix/howto_transclude.php
This definitely works in Firefox and IE6 but I didn't test others.
This page just includes an iframe and the source for the iframe is http://wiki.eclipse.org/transclude.php?page=XXXX
Where XXXX is the wiki page to be accessed. A non-skinned content-only wiki page is delivered as part of document. There are some shortcomings:
1.) The IFrame has to be of a fixed size because IFrame's don't have any way to auto-size based on content.
2.) In order for the pages to break out of the IFrame I had to edit the DOM to retarget all the URLs to the top. Trying to distinguis local URLs from remote ones is probably not possible so all URLs, wiki and otherwise, behave the same way with respect to the IFrame.
Is this an acceptable solution? At this point it looks like the only one we are likely to get working any time soon.
I forgot to point out in reference to shortcoming #1: the Javascript security model prevents me from finding out the size of the content in the IFrame.
Closing as fixed... This seems to be a good solution (or should I say -- the only solution?)
Moving to Community/Website

bug.short_desc: Eclipse & SWT/Cairo on Linux Romanian causes JVM segfault

long_desc.thetext:
1. Install Eclipse 3.2 with all of the NL language packs 2. Follow the SWT workspace setup (http://www.eclipse.org/swt/eclipse.php) 3. Create a new Java project based on Snippet10.java (http://dev.eclipse.org/viewcvs/index.cgi/~checkout~/org.eclipse.swt.snippets/src/org/eclipse/swt/snippets/Snippet10.java) 4. Run Snippet10 5. JVM cores with the following: javaw: cairo-ft-font.c:680: _cairo_ft_unscaled_font_set_scale: Assertion `error == 0' failed. JVMDG217: Dump Handler is Processing Signal 6 - Please Wait. JVMDG303: JVM Requesting Java core file JVMDG304: Java core file written to /root/workspace/swttest/javacore.20060918.165541.3854.txt JVMDG215: Dump Handler has Processed Error Signal 6.
We know Eclipse on Linux does not support Romanian directly but ideally it should not core and should be able to default to English for the fonts.

Created an attachment (id=50507) Javacore of crash
We have been experiencing similar problems when using GMF on Linux SUSE. When the user selects certain fonts (for example 'Adobe Courier'), eclipse crashes. Doing some tracing it seems that it is related to a bug in the Cairo libraries. From what I can see, SWT uses Cairo for anti-aliasing of fonts. I have attached java dump of our scenario.
This issue may be related to the cairo bug https://bugs.freedesktop.org/show_bug.cgi?id=8104. In this bug, the crashing is limited to machines with Hyperthreading or Dual Cores. I have tested the GMF scenario on a non-Hyperthreading machine, yet the crashing persists.

Revised steps to reproduce: - change LANG environment variable to ro_RO.UTF-8 - start Eclipse - run Snippet 11.
Wayne, what version of cairo are you using? Please attach output from rpm -q gtk2 glib2 pango cairo Are you actually running on a romanian linux system or did you do something similer to changing your LANG environment variable?

"rpm -q gtk2 glib2 pango cairo" output: gtk2-2.4.13-18 glib2-2.4.7-1 pango-1.6.0-9 package cairo is not installed
We are relying on the libcairo-swt.so packaged in the org.eclipse.swt.gtk.linux.x86_3.2.0.v3232m.jar included with Eclipse 3.2. According to the about_files/about_cairo.html included in the JAR this is Cairo 1.0.2
As for my Linux system - it is a RedHat Enterprise Linux 4 Update 3 system with no additional RedHat Network Updates installed at this time. During installation of this system I chose for all keyboard layouts and all locales to be available. To change to a different locale I login and use the Gnome Language application which executes /usr/bin/system-config-language and choose Romanian. I then logout, and on the login screen choose Romanian from the Language popup menu before logging back in. At this point anything with a Romanian translation appears in Romanian.

The snippet runs correctly on fedora core 5 (gtk2-2.8.20-1, glib2-2.10.3-1, pango-1.12.3-1, cairo-1.0.4-1).
Is this only a problem when using Romanian or does the crash occur using other languages as well?

I have not personally tested all of the languages we support and cannot say for certain all the languages it occurs on. Our test team has indicated problems on Romanian and Ukrainian resulting in the cairo assertion I originally reported.
This appears to be a bug in Freetype. I have not been able to reproduce the bug while running freetype-2.1.10. Reducing the severity as this does not affect supported platforms.
Updating freetype to version 2.1.10 does fix this bug for the GMF scenario.

Updating to freetype 2.1.10 does prevent the JVM from crashing using the Snippet10 project I referenced, however the snippet isn't 100% correct. When running in English the text "SWT" is drawn diagonally across the window but in Romanian the text is not drawn. Just wanted to point this out.
Overall we agree with the answer as updating freetype also allows our application to launch correctly and we do not appear to be having any font/text issues.
This bug can be closed as needed - thanks for the assistance in tracking down the culprit.
Resolving as WORKSFORME.

bug.short_desc: Provide ability to exclude a directory from the Target Platform

bug.short_desc: Problem on updating struct type variable

long_desc.thetext: After step, struct type variable cannot be updated its members on Variable view. If you changed the stackframe on Debug View, then the variable will be updated. The problem is that variable label on Variable View cannot be updated. It still referenced the old variable label even if it has disposed. If you changed the stackframe on Debug View, the variable label on Variable view can be updated by refreshing. Then it can point to correct value.

What do you mean by 'variable label'? Does this problem occur when you have a structure open in the Variable View (i.e. displaying the members of the structure) and one of the members changes? How does CDT get around the problem?
Why are the members disposed? Why does this work for CDT?

--test --aint --achar
If parent (test) is changed, its members (aint and achar) will be disposed. If its member is changed, its value will be changed only.
In CDT, it will get aint or achar changed only. While PTP will get test changed even if only aint or achar is changed. We used AIF in PTP, there is only one variable (test) and it contains all members. In CDT, each member is individual.
Is it possible to fetch the whole structure again and update members that have changed?

Temporary fixed this problem. For example,
-struct1 -v1 -v2
MIVar will be used in GDB when any variables are changed. struct1 -- var1 v1 -- var1.v1 v2 -- var1.v2
If var1.v2 is changed, I will find the mapping var1 to struct1 and send event with the name of variable (struct1.v1). In ptp design, it uses AIF to present variable and value. AIF of variable struct1 will contain AIF of its members (v1 and v2). If var1.v2 is changed, it needs to get the whole AIF of struct1. Now I changed, it will get AIF of struct1.v1 only and replace will old AIF value. The problem is that AIF of struct1 still contain old AIF of v1, so AIF value of v1 is different with its parent AIF value.
I also changed full name of variable. For example, the full name of v1 is struct1.v1 and v2 is struct1.v2. This change can be easier to find the changed variable.
This seems to work ok now.

bug.short_desc: Forms don't fill out values for required attributes anymore

long_desc.thetext:
3.3M2 test candidate
This one also falls under 'One step forward, two steps back':
When you create elements on the Extensions page, required attributes no longer get default values generated.
defaults are generated fine when using the source page.

This bug is a side effect of the fix for 151109. The problem lies in whether or not to set the parent element when creating an element.
There is one important line of code that was taken out during the fix for 151109. In PluginNodeDocumentFactory.createElement(), we no longer call "node.setParentNode((IDocumentNode)parent);". If you add this line back in, the Forms fills in required attributes just fine.
Unfortunately, this breaks the content assist. Because, with the same fix for 151109, the element created needs to have no parent. On line 90 of DocumentHandler, node.getParent now does not equal null. To make content assist work correctly, remove the line in the paragraph above and it will now enter the if statement on line 90.
Since I am unfamiliar with this area of code, if we want to fix this bug for M2, we need Wassim to take a quick look at this bug to figure out whether we include the node.setParentNode(..) line, and if so, how to make content assist work. If he does not have time, I can look into this for post M2 as to not introduce a bug at the last minute.

My investigation has led me to the same conclusion as Brian.
It is not immediately obvious to me why XML content assist is broken when parents are stored in the model. I've isolated the problem down to the modifyModel() method of org.eclipse.pde.internal.ui.editor.contentassist.XMLCompletionProposal.java
The comparison of offsets using the model seem to be thrown off when trying to search for the right IPluginParent and associated ISchemaElement used as input to the XMLInsertionComputer to generate the attributes values.
Please let me know if you decide to put back in the line node.setParentNode((IDocumentNode)parent); and then you can punt this bug back to me, to fix the content assist problem and perform some necessary code clean-up and commenting on the modifyModel() method.
Since the fix involves code we are not familiar with, Mike and I will look into this one post M2.

Thanks for looking into this, guys.
The current code is actually correct. the parent node should not be set until the parent.add(child) call is made.
This unfortunately broke the functionality on the Extensions page.
In NewElementAction.run(), if we switch the parent.add(..) statement with the initializeAttributes() statements, it works fine. But, the UI only updates after add(); it does not update after initializeAttributes. So the fields are initialized correctly, but still show blank.
That is why the only solution I could come up with was to set the parent node explicitly prior to initializeAttributes(). This solves all problems.
Incidentally, the Extension page code needs a major cleanup. we should do it some time in 3.3.

bug.short_desc: Copy/Paste j2ee projects not the same as Rename

Now we have two projects: - ejb-copy that is copy/pasted from the original 'ejb' project; - ejb-rename that is the renamed original 'ejb' project.

The described inconsistency may cause problems later on deployment, because if the user duplicates j2ee projects with copy/paste then he/she might expect that the deploy name changes automatically, too (the same way as with rename).

Finally, after looking at the source code, this bug should be really in jst.j2ee. The ProjectRenameOperation is in the org.eclipse.jst.j2ee plugin and it should be applied accordingly for the copy/paste operation.

executing a copy/paste generates distinct resource change events from a rename
our existing refactoring support was only designed to handle renames and deletes; additional logic will be needed to cover this case
The changes for this are not trivial (and therefore involve some risk of destabilization); not going to try for 2.0 at this point

long_desc.thetext: Created an attachment (id=50456) The ICO File looking bad
SSQ and/or CAR to investigate.

WinXP Icon issue - https://bugs.eclipse.org/bugs/show_bug.cgi?id=27722 (Mark dup) Linux Icon issue - https://bugs.eclipse.org/bugs/show_bug.cgi?id=34980
I think the first problem might be the same as this...but is was marked duplicate of a linux bug for some reason?

OK, here's what's happening.
The ico file actually contains 6 icons, of varying sizes and depths. The first one is 16 x 16 depth 4, and the last one is 48 x 48 depth 8. The first one looks awful, and the last one looks really nice.
It is up to the application to choose which one it wants to display. It looks like IE is just choosing the first (the ugly one), Firefox chooses the 3rd (happens to be 16 x 16 depth 8... looks nice, but small), File Explorer also uses the 3rd, while Paint and Windows Picture Viewer choose the 6th (the nice 48 x 48 depth 8 guy).
In SWT, if you use new Image(display, stream); or new ImageData(stream); or new ImageData(filename); you will just get the first icon. You can use ImageLoader to get all 6 of the icons, and then choose the one you want.
It is, however, interesting that if you use new Image(display, filename); then the native loading code selects the nice 48 x 48 depth 8 icon. I am not sure if we should be making any decisions regarding which icon is "best" in our non-native icon loading code... Silenio, what do you think?
Sorry Eric, just got your comment. No, this is not the same problem as those other 2 bugs. It has nothing to do with alpha.
The image constructor should pick the first icon the same way the ImageData constructor does. We have to see if we can override the GDI+ behavior.

I dunno - it's kind of interesting that the native GDI+ constructor picks a "nice" icon. Perhaps the ImageData constructor should emulate the native one?
Did you by chance see any doc on exactly what the GDI+ code is looking for? It seems that it just chose the largest icon with the greatest depth that the display can handle... if that's all, we can do that, too. It is probably what people usually want. Of course, we could break a bunch of old code if we do that <g>.
A "nice" size depends on the usage. For example, a "nice" size for an icon in a table is not a "nice" size for the Alt+Tab icon.
We could choose the icon that has the highest bit depth the display can handle and is the same size as the first one, if such exists. That appears to be what Firefox is doing (see comment 5).

Anyhow, for those of you who are interested in this bug, please note that the lesson here is that for icons, use ImageLoader to load an array of icons, and then choose the one you want based on size and bit depth. There are often multiple icons in an ICO file.

Can we close this bug, then?

bug.short_desc: ElementTypeRegistry fails to load element type in some particular case

long_desc.thetext:
I have two gmf-generated plugins for uml2 metamodel. The first one defines element type for Model EClass in the client context A.editingdomain (the Model is mapped to the canvas for this editor)
The second one does not define element type for Model EClass, instead it defines the element type for uml.Package. It is defined in different client context -- say, B.editing.domain.

In case if the A plugin presents, the ElementTypeRegistry#getMetamodelTypeDescriptor() successfully finds descriptors collection at the line 634. This collection contains the Model element type from plugin A, context A and can not be matched for client context B. Thus, the "for" loop at the lines 639-646 does not return anything, and the control flow immediately fails to the line 672 -- return null.
I hope that in this case the code from "else" clause should be executed (like in the case when plugin A is disabled and collection = null) to allow searching for super types.

The user visible consequence of this bug is:
At the gmf-generated uml class diagram (the B one) it is impossible to create top-level elements in case is plugin for state diagram (the A) is installed/present in development workspace.

bug.short_desc: Improve javadoc of Control#addKeyListener(..) to tell about changed traversal behavior

long_desc.thetext:
I20060919-0010
- remove source attachment from rt.jar - open java.lang.Integer => Focus is nowhere => Tab, Ctrl+Tab, F12 all don't give the focus back
In 3.2 the initial focus was on the editor tab. I would expect the focus to be on the Attach Source button (if it exists), or in the text area with the decompiled text.

In the 'no source' case we do set the focus on the source attachment form (a Control) and it works for me on Linux and on other WinXP machines using I20060919-0010.
Markus, if you have more info then please add them.
Moving to SWT for comment - any idea?
If you add a key listener, then you expect to get focus and take part in tab traversal, even when you are not a leaf widget. Controls such as CTabFolder rely on this behavior.

I only found a specification for this behavior in the Javadoc of KeyEvent. I think you should add a big warning to the Javadoc of Control#addKeyListener(KeyListener) as well, since that is the actual call that causes this subtle change.
Reopening as a request for better javadoc then. The blurb in KeyEvent's javadoc should be repeated in Control#addKeyListener(..).

The convention is for the documentation to be in the event. In this case, I think we should also say something in the addListener() because it affects the behavior of the widget.
NOTE: @see XXXEvent etc. is missing from all addXXXListener() methods. Should we also add them to the removeXXXListener methods()?
> Should we also add them to the removeXXXListener methods()? I don't think that's necessary, since you always have to call addKeyListener first. I'm fine with the fix as released in HEAD.
